People that you still love?

No, I don't think you defaulted on them.
I think that you had to act on your own needs.
What good is it if you were captured, picked up by the feds, only to be a good friend to this person?
And I didn't write to him.
She named Dewey.
Dewey was the guy who gave me that five cent match and got the job in Beavers.
Ed and the bosses.
I don't write to them, but I consider them good friends.
When it comes to the actual closeness, I stop.

I want to be closer, but I stop.
He's a great artist.
He hangs in galleries.

He was your student?
He was my tennis student.
We trade.
I teach him tennis and he teach me.
We bartered.
No cash.
That's good.
That's good.
He teach me how to paint.
And, of course, Slim Mayfair.
I just mentioned him.
He's a marvelous person.
Great, great Western.
Big heart.
And even my boss, Bill Klein.
You know, I could be much closer.
I would be much closer.
I think I would be much closer with almost anybody.
Bill Klein gave us kind of a start in our tennis shop, and that was 20 years later when we were really going into that venture and extremely undercapitalized.
Undercapitalized.
I mean, ridiculously undercapitalized.
We had to stock the shop, and then it said, oh, well, why don't I call up Bill Klein, my former boss, I've been seeing him for many, many years, who...
He was up at Sugar Bowl, but he had a shop at Gary Dilley Square in San Francisco.
And I was cringed to death.
You have to throw yourself on the mercy of somebody else.
Yeah, that's not my style.
You're too independent for that.
So anyway, we did that.
We went up there, and sure enough, his brother was in the shop.
He gave us a stash.
Well, we paid for it, but the very idea of taking something out of somebody else's shop.
He gave it to us wholesale, so at least we could make a profit when we sold it.
He had stocked our first shop in the resort area.
Really nice.
He would go to Austria and buy his sweaters and stuff, you see, every year.
So he had the finest clothes.
So that was his first business.

We didn't quite make enough money to hire somebody.
Well, we would a couple of times, but not... We were not quite as...

his inability, in his own mind, to enter into a contract negotiation.

Yeah, the aggressive part of him was out there on the tennis court or some other place, but I never could get hold of it in some of these other areas that were pretty important.

Yeah, now I can see why he doesn't want to sign his name on a contract.
So, in so many ways, it sort of turned out we did all the right things for all the wrong reasons.
Just lucked out.
Yeah, lucked out.
That's exactly it.
If you don't have any luck, just forget everything I ever told you.
And so I would always say, well, okay, but never mind that.
There's something else, some other thing to go on to.
Let's not really dwell on that.
I don't really want to deal with that.
Let's just go on to something else.
What we're going to go on to soon is we're going to get some food in the candy.
You know, I deal in contracts every day.
I have to read to find printed the specifications.
If I miss one word, you could lose thousands of dollars, you know.

When the walls were feet high on each side, I could have been just run over.
I don't know why I did it.
I just really took a real chance to get killed by an oncoming train, but I figured I might be able to hear it.
But there was my only, I couldn't get back any other way.
The roads were still closed, and they stayed closed for another month before anybody could move over the mountain.
So it was kind of a very trying experience because here I was almost in the limelight and, you know, virtue being discovered and what to do.
And then sometimes you do some, most of the time I run in a situation like that.
Just run, you know, not necessarily any big plan.
Did you get back to the cabin?
Yeah, went back and they were still rescuing people, dogs that had been snowed in in the cabins, you know.
So it went on for a long time.
The road to Reno didn't open for another four weeks.
I have some nice 8mm movies at home, in color, some of that stuff.
Were you afraid that somebody might come up during the month that you were back in the cabin?
I don't think anybody, there was no way for any inexperienced person to come in.
No, I felt very safe on that, but I thought maybe the publicity of the picture or something, might somebody, might be around to find, to recognize me.
Nobody recognized that picture.
I'm actually going to show you a copy of it.
Right, right.
And you twisted your face?
Well, I did, more or less, inside.
I thought it was intense stuff.
Let me ask you about going back to the camp, some of the POW camps.
I need to feel more what your day was like.
You were a camp translator in each of these camps.
You became the translator just by habit, or that you were the official translator at each place along the way?
It was pretty informal.
I don't think you got appointed or anything.
You simply got called in when there was any need for translation.
It was structured in as much as you had to get up at a certain time, six o'clock or whatever it was.
for meals and inspections and reports.
I guess they had to report to the American Office of Charge.
And then they pretty much tried to have activity like you might have in any youth
organization or camp just to keep people busy with projects.
Woodworking?
Woodworking, painting, letter writing, reading.
Did you do some of those things?
Yeah.
I did some art work.
You walk around in groups and circles, like around the camp, you can walk all day as long as you don't touch the wires.
Too close together.
What would you talk about walking around?
Because we're talking about a period of a couple of years.
Yeah.
Did you fall in with the same bunch of fellows each time, or were there people that stuck out in your mind along the way?
That one picture guy, the artist, I would always gravitate to those people that did something artistic.
Painting, woodworking, something like that.
Sports, a little bit of soccer I might have played.
And then that one can't be a lot to play some tennis.
I had a tennis tournament.
Wow.
No, we didn't really do, and then some places we had to work.
We had to, I was in one place, I was a draftsman, you know, I did some drafting work for some engineering department that was nearby.
Some army engineering department?
Yeah, army engineering.
So, we did have, a lot of guys had jobs, and they liked their jobs, you know, they kept them busy.
But it was, with us, it was pretty much volunteer whether we wanted to work or not.
The offices didn't work at all, and I heard, you know, they were in separate camps.
With the non-com offices, it was more or less volunteer basis.
But I remember Fort Knox, I worked in the hospital.
I was probably in orderly cleaning and stuff.
I'm not saying anything about anything else.
It had to be some kind of a service child.
And mostly, I was invariably drawn into translating for other people.
because there were not enough English-speaking prisoners, at least not enough.
They might know some words, but I usually ended up with that job because there was always a problem of some kind.
I want them to do this and explain this to them.
And there was a lot of conversation with the guards and the Americans that was always fascinating.
about what they were doing.
They asked us questions.
What was it like?
What do you think?
What our feelings were.
We had quite a bit in the beginning, especially.
We had a lot of conversation.
I do remember one guard telling me that, I told you that about the millionaires, that there were some millionaires in this community.
And I couldn't figure out how that could be.
And they talked to us about, not too much about politics, or trying to think in terms of politics.
It wasn't really all that much.
They might...
and talk about Hitler or something like that, and they'd laugh and say, yeah, that, you know.
Because we didn't, we really didn't know what they knew about Hitler and what we knew about Hitler.
We really, probably, we would be talking past each other in most cases, I would say.
But they knew about it, and when we were told about it, we're not the same, you know, so.
But they wanted to know a lot about us, and we were curious about them.
And as a rule, the Americans are, you know, by our standards, I think they're very polite anyway.
Polite people by nature.
They want to know what you're doing and what you're, if they can, you know, what your needs are.
That's, they're natural that way.
I've found always that they're out much more polite than
And I think a lot of times if that came across, some schlocky guys would misunderstand that
take advantage of it, maybe.
I'm sure somebody would do that and snicker about it, but they totally misunderstand good manners are really interesting to other people.
They would misunderstand that.
You can't educate them.
It wasn't for me to educate them.
Was there any guard in particular that you knew like, or commanding officer that you remember in particular?
No, I do remember one guy who I believe, now in retrospect, was probably an intelligence officer.
He came, he was assigned all of a sudden to the staff, and he would get very chummy with us, you know, and laugh and joke.
I had a feeling he was, in fact, to the point where we were wondering whether he was straight or not.
And he did take me into a room once and had a conversation with me.
And I had a feeling that later on, I think he was probably going to tell us what's up.
He spoke in German or he was speaking in English?
No, I probably spoke in English.
But I had no idea.

at the time we didn't know about this that never made itself felt you never had any uh well you said to the nazis whatever whoever they were were statement to themselves yeah they later on as things got
The news got worse and worse.
They did get grim and they kind of stayed to themselves and would say, I don't believe any of that stuff because of what came through this news.
I can't believe any of that.
When they couldn't believe it, do you mean that the battle was going badly for Germany?
Yeah, yeah, yeah.
The battles would, you know, instead of winning these battles, we were losing these battles, you see.
So, and things got very quiet, actually.
It was just kind of like a wet blanket in the whole camp, you might say.
because all the news was bad all the time.
Were there any escape committees or anything like that that you remember?
That's what I thought.
It wasn't well organized.
No.
Never.
Never talked to anybody that wanted to escape or wanted me to escape.
Nothing like that in my camp.
I'm sure they had it in some camps.
I didn't realize there were that many camps in that many places.
I'm sure that...
different people run, and you get a different mixture of people.
And some of them had a lot of great education, even, from what I read in your book.
They had, you know, got an education that served them well later on.
Theater.
Did you have concerts there, or plays?
Yeah, we had music there.
We had instruments.
We had concerts.
And so...
A lot of people were involved with that.
Were the concerts by people from the outside, or was it just you?
No, I was just German.
They would provide the instruments, and that's all they need, and they'd go into it and have concerts and have plays.
They always tried to come up with something to entertain ourselves, mostly.
Did you sell handicrafts to the guards?
Yeah, we would sell handicrafts, not so much to the guard maybe, but amongst ourselves.
We would make toilet bags.
One guy was good in leather making things.
We'd barter, sometimes with the guards, sometimes amongst ourselves.
What would an average day have been, if you could reconstruct an average day?
Get up early, get up late?
Get up early, get up early, 6 o'clock, roll call, breakfast.
Everybody outside be counted?
Counted, every morning counted, roll call.
Was it a large barrack generally, or just a small hut?
It was a large compound, but it was always made into smaller areas.
It wasn't just one huge burning.
When you could go through on certain days, you were allowed to pass and visit others.
But it was kind of sectional.
Sections.
So many barracks in one section and then another section.
So you'd have your work hall breakfast, and then once you had a job, you went to work.
And you either took your lunch, it was ready,
kitchen had already made and the ones that stayed behind had to have to be barracks cleaning every day same routine cleaning areas outside inside by that time it's 10 11 o'clock

you could get either into, if you didn't have a job, you'd go back to your own project, you'd have a couple hours to go to your own project, or you could stay outside, walk around, talk to your friends, usually getting some exercise by walking around the canyon.
And by that time,
came close to lunch, lunchtime.
Then you had, they had some kind of an activity, like a meeting.
They set up meetings to meet at the hall, to discuss certain, mostly,
Something that might concern our relationship with the American system, the officers.
Problems that have come up, we've got to stop doing this, we've got complaints, such and such.
So there was a certain amount of structure which was passed on.
from the Americans to us, and our, the guys that took, that were in command, these were mostly, mostly they were professional soldiers, career soldiers.
They did it like a, like it was, like they were at home, you know.
They told us, this is, this is, come to the area, we've got to stop doing this, and we've got to shape up a little, this is.
So there was an interaction between the prisoner and the guards and the officers.
And they, every day, had to have, that was something that they wanted us to do or change.
So you knew you were constantly being watched and monitored.
You felt, you know, that there was somebody counting and so forth.
Who would you have taken orders from in the camp?
Mostly from our own non-com, the oldest ranking non-com officers.
They posted the times and the meetings.
It was the same as a military operation, maybe not as strict and as rigid as it would in boot camp, but it kept always running.
It was always run on the military.
Were there fights or were there special problems?
There were personality problems.

gravitate toward the people that they liked and they formed little cliques and their properties into politics and things like that like you have in any fairly large group of people but all in all these were all non-com officers so they all kind of had a lot of personal pride in their rank and in their you know so it was very little did you usually uh
So in one camp you were a draftsman, someplace else you worked outside picking fruit or picking things?
No, I never had to go outside in the field and do any of that.
I read about it, but I was not in that.
No contract work for businesses or anything like that?
No.
Just that one possible orderly type job I had, and then the draftsman job.
Then mostly my job would be to be there when this guy, the non-com officer in charge was in a meeting with the American officer.
I would have to be there because it was always something they didn't understand.
So I was engaged in that.
Once we were dismissed from that, then I was on my own.
I could do what I wanted to.
That sounds like fun.
It sounds a little boring.
It was.
It was boring and not very boring.
We weren't talking about the honeymoon part.
I heard you walk in on the word boring and I thought... Would you like a... Oh, that'd be great.
Or if we have some more vodka.
No, I've actually put the wine on this.
Would you like a plane or something?
I used to love planes.
Schweppes and a Tequena.
Yeah, that would be nice.
That makes it kind of a spritzer, you know.
It makes a spritzer.
Yes, yes.
I didn't have forgotten about that until this German college.
You always had a spritzer.
In taking on the name Wiles, it's the one letter that would be difficult to pronounce.
Exactly.
Part of it was emotional because this migrant laborer that took me along because, you know, as I've explained, it's easier to get jobs when you drive up to a farmer and say you have two hands.
You can contract, for instance, pruning or in the wintertime you prune the plum orchards and get rid of all the external branches.
One guy couldn't possibly prune
Eight, ten acres.
Two guys can get something done.
And he had the car.
And he looked like my brother.
And he looked like my brother.
He was the same type, really.
And as I said, I always looked for similarities to make me feel at ease and at home.
This morning, I saw this lady in the lobby, and I thought she looked like my sister.
I do this all the time.
It's similar.
It's kind of a game I play.
I entertain myself.
And he was a real nice guy, low-key.
He had been divorced, or his wife ran out on him, and took up with an officer while he was overseas.
He was a discharge.
And he would get on these crime jokes.
He was still in love with his wife, so he would get very sad about that little break up.
He would tell me about it.
Then he'd go to the nearest bar and he'd drink up.
I wouldn't see him, and he'd drink up everything we'd made.
And I'd sit in the hotel room looking at the walls.
And then we'd sometimes have lunch in the bar with a sandwich and a straight shot.
In one of those honky tonk bars in the valley and all up and down.
Honky tonk bar.
The music playing, the western music playing in the jerk box.
But I could never get any money ahead because he was the one that made the deal with the farmer and the farmer paid him.
He drank it up.
He drank it up and he only gave me rent.
pocket money, say.
How much would you make working on a farm?
How much would you be going through?
Well, we would probably average, the highest I ever made was $20 a day picking cherries.
I would probably say we'd average $8 to $10 a day, maybe.
Whatever chores we had to do.

so it was about a dollar a dollar i guess my father big chair told me a story about picking cherries once in the old country and he said that the only stipulation to all the kids that they hired was they had to keep singing and as soon as they stopped singing the performance would come and find them because i mean they were eating the fruit so they had to keep singing it didn't matter what song just everybody has to sing the moment they heard somebody up there stop singing
how he was eating.
You could eat all they were delicious, those cherries, those peaches.
But once I got a little money ahead, I split, socked it away, you know, a dollar here and a dollar there.
But I felt now that I had, I knew this was a real American name.
This Peter Peterson,
was just not a person.
I couldn't.
Oh, the cork popped, honey.
Sure.

I felt I wasn't in the mainstream.
I was too European and too much like an immigrant kind of thing.
And I thought, I'd never heard a name like that before.
Dennis Wilds.
And it was also a challenge, as you pointed out, that W is the hardest thing to learn.
And I started, and I said, why don't I take that name that's going to make me learn that letter?
Because I have to learn that letter.
When they say my name, I have to get into it, really.
It took the hardest way, the toughest choice, and left the easy one for later.
Did you ever run across his records?
Or did your names ever cross anywhere?
Someone say, Dennis, well, I knew a guy who lived down in the valley with the same name.
No, in fact, everybody says they had never heard that name before.
Once or twice, maybe, someone says he did.
And I look in the phone book.
Do you want that?
I like the one for cameos.
Every time, almost every time somebody would say it, they never heard that name.
Dispelling or anything.
W-H-I-L-E-S. Where's that guy today, do you think?
I have no idea.
Probably still picking fruit.
Although he was about 10 years older, so he'd be 70.
70 years old, so I don't think he'd be climbing any trees.
Where was that that you...
Did you spend that time with him?
All up and down California, San Joaquin Valley, following the crew.
One season?
One season.
What year was it, do you think?
When you left Peter Peterson?
Peter Peterson.
It was Peter Peterson.
Probably 48, 49.
Did you really feel yourself as Peter Peterson?
No.
I never got really warmed up.
That's just...
They actually took that and they spotted it.
It was a great idea because they immediately said, oh, you're Norwegian or something, see?
But that, to me, then I had to really be Norwegian.
And then I was, you see, actually in... Typecast is something that you had to be.
Yeah, but I didn't know anything how to be it, you see.
So it was two... Everybody made me immediately typecast me.
Yes.
Well, once I switched to Dennis Walsh, there was... That's such a neutral name, nobody even knows where it's from.
Yes.
But the...
You needed Peter Peterson during the accent.
Yes, that was ideal.
Nobody questioned my accent.
As a typical Peter Peterson guy.
So once you felt more comfortable, that's when you changed.
You must have felt that you could make it in English with no trouble, because it was time to learn.
I was trying to improve, and that W thing, I felt that was a good idea.
I didn't want to be a lumberjack Norwegian forever and ever, having had that accident already, cutting down my trees.
And that close call of somebody wanting me to run a lumber mill for them.
Yes, yes.
What was that about?
Yeah, there was a real weird, this Chinchilla Brothers had done some fruit packing for them outside of Stockton.
And then I went off to the snow country again, and when I came back, my red-headed landlady said, you know, they've been looking for you.
They had a chance to buy a lumber mill and they wanted you to run it.
I was typecast as a knowledgeable lumberjack, I guess.
Which I was not, so... Did you ever have to go up and top trees and... Yeah, in that one time I went to Medford to pick apples and they weren't ready.
And being that I was Peter Peters and they thought, why don't you go out and cut some trees down for us and make some logs.
Hmm.
Terrible mosquitoes and... Yeah, I don't recall the mosquitoes.
But this was with the...
With the prongs in your feet and spikes?
No, I didn't have to climb up.
They were fairly small trees.
I could cut them from the base, from the bottom.
This is before chainsaws.
Yeah, before chainsaws.
Just big, big sharp legs.
But, you know, I wouldn't know how to sharpen in eggs and things like that.
And pretty soon I would be...
Also, Peter Peterson was good while it lasted.
While it lasted, yeah.
And then when your English became better, then you risked another jump to then as well.
How did you come up with the, how did you build a past?
A past?
Yeah, how did you build, how did you sit down and say, well, Connecticut School of the Boys.
I went to the library in Stockton and studied the Northeast.
little towns around Lake Placid.
And the schools, looked up some schools that I could, might have gone to that looked interesting.
And I found that school for boys.
That might explain a few things.
It was different enough
It was not a regular school because I just never understood the school system, the public school system.
I could never remember the grades.
Do they start at eight or go down?
Do they start at one and go up?
So this way, you went all schooling in one place.
Yeah.
It simplifies it.
And then an orphan, you know.
And in a school for boys, that indicates I was probably Catholic.
That's true, yes.
Did you go to church while you were on the, while you were out, after you left the camp?
No, but I went to church while I was in camp.
On Sundays, yes.
We went to church.
But once you left camp,
I'm trying to think what churches I went to.
Yes, I did go to some of the churches.
I went to some of them.
But I didn't know what church I was in.
There were so many different religions.
Baptists, you know.
People would ask me to go along.
But a Catholic church, no?
No, never went to a Catholic.
So you never went to confession?
No.
Mostly Baptist type.
The kind that we didn't have in Germany.
If you had gone to confession, would you have said, I'm going to escape?
Even in a confessional.
It wouldn't have said I'm a prisoner, fugitive.
You don't take religion that seriously.
That's good.
That was a personal thing.
This whole thing is very personal.
I didn't want to involve anybody.
I didn't want to ask for any help from anybody or put them into jeopardy.
And don't put myself into jeopardy.
Yeah, it took a long time to get over some of that, you know, that really
independence of not taking anybody and then not letting anybody get close.
But I finally realized you have to get close to someone, especially the opposite sex.
It just is not natural to do that kind of thing.
And I could see these loners, these lone fruit pickers, these old men, I could see their fate, what happens to them.
You know, they're Schicksal.
They're Schicksal.
And the drinking that they do, the solitary drinking, the sadness that they talk about their whatever short marriage they had.
I was married for five years and not alone.
And that was it.
It was the highlight of their life.
And then it was more or less downhill.
on an emotional basis for them.
They kept on working and living, but...
Inside they were dead.
They were dead.
And I kept reading, you know.
I never stopped reading.
I'm constantly first to how to do books.
And especially, you know, these books that relate to
to get yourself upright, to get yourself squared away psychologically.
Unfortunately, a lot of Americans are into that.
Unfortunately, they're into that.
So there are plenty of books available on that subject.
And just keep reading and reading and finding similarities.
Look for something that I can apply.
to get myself straightened out so that I don't go off to deep end, I don't start drinking, or I don't get frustrated and violent and whatever.
And all these books help me.
The Power of Positive Thinking and The Art of Conversation and all that.
And you would just carry that book with you?
Yeah, I had him, still had him when I got married.
I just opened the library, but I couldn't get anybody interested in it, in the family.
I wanted my kids, I wanted Cheryl and Mark to read it, but they were just not into it.
They didn't need to get into the mainstream as badly as you.
Let me ask you this.
What did you think might happen to you if something did go wrong?
Let's say that you were, the worst came to worst, and the feds
somehow found you?
What was the worst thing that happened?
I'm trying to imagine what the fear is.
The fear is just someone getting you.
Or the fear is, or did you think farther and say, well, if they get me, they're going to put me in jail.
I don't want to be in a small room with bars on it.
But that will only be temporary because eventually they'll take me in front of a judge.
They'll give me some sort of punishment.
I'll probably be sent back to Europe.
Maybe.
All right, so I'll be in Europe.
Well, I'd certainly want to go back to Europe.
It's almost the same as a prison.
I see.
The way I look at Europe.
I see.
To me, it's just a small little place on the map, not any larger than California.
Right.
So there's a fear of every one of those things, being captured,
jail, the trial, and the shipment back.
So there isn't any good thing in there.
I see what you're saying.
I see no good thing at all.
The humiliation of one day here you're a free man, you walk the streets as a free man, and the next day you're a criminal.
